# File Organisation

## New features go in new files when they have a clear boundary

Create a new file when the new code:
- Is a new tab or section in the admin dashboard (e.g. `app/admin/quality.py`)
- Is a new cron/script with its own purpose (e.g. `scripts/generate_quality_digest.py`)
- Is a new Flask blueprint or route group
- Would push an existing file past ~500 lines

Stay in the existing file when:
- It's a small addition (a new helper, a column, a field)
- It's tightly coupled to existing logic in that file
- A new file would only be 20–30 lines

## Admin dashboard modules

New admin tabs belong in `app/admin/<tab_name>.py` with a `render_<tab>_tab()` function and a `register_<tab>_routes(bp)` function. Register both in `app/admin/__init__.py`.

## Scripts

New one-off or cron scripts go in `scripts/`. New Railway cron configs go in `operator/railway.<name>.toml`.

## Never grow these files further

| File | Why |
|------|-----|
| `app/admin/__init__.py` | Already 1,900+ lines — delegate to submodules |
| `app/storage/postgres.py` | Add migrations to existing tuples only, no new logic |
